STEP 6 — eBPF TELEMETRY (Nexus probes)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

eBPF lets you trace kernel events with nanosecond precision and ZERO
overhead to the trading path (probes run in a separate kernel context).

  # Install bpftrace:
  apt install bpftrace

  # Trace TCP packet latency for our WebSocket connection:
  bpftrace -e '
  kprobe:tcp_rcv_established {
      @ts[pid] = nsecs;
  }
  kretprobe:tcp_rcv_established /@ts[pid]/ {
      $lat = nsecs - @ts[pid];
      if ($lat > 500000) {  // alert on >500μs
          printf("LATENCY SPIKE: %d μs (PID %d)\n", $lat/1000, pid);
      }
      delete(@ts[pid]);
  }'

  # Integration with Nexus monitoring:
  # Pipe bpftrace output to ClickHouse latency table
  # Alert via Slack/PagerDuty when P99 latency > 500μs

